Fix frame collisions between extended and standard frames

If an extended frame was having an ID that would be <= 0x7FF, then it would collide with the ID of a standard frame

This is fixed by setting the top bit i.e. OR'ing the frame by 0x80000000 similar to what is done in DBC files and in the Linux kernel

Fixes #654

Merge pull request #733 from Lauszus/fix/database_extended_id

Fix frame collisions between extended and standard frames

Merge pull request #741 from zariiii9003/codegen_node

Fix compiler error for code generated with --node arg
bugfix logreader: use system timezone instead of utc to parse timestamps
more typing and fixed wrong typing of DataFrame.timestamp
logreader: added optional timezone argument for Parser

logreader: refactoring to reduce redundancy and improve maintainability of candump parsers

I have factored out most of the parsing into a new base class CandumpBasePattern.
Just the pattern and the parsing of timestamps remains in the child classes.

logreader: refactoring to reduce redundancy and improve maintainability of PCAN trace parsers

Each version now inherits the unpack method from the previous version.
I have moved the doc strings from the unpack methods into the doc strings of the class.

bugfix: don't override previous test

bugfix for commit a57a7084441a67cd2759ffaf5cad33afa4b6bb01

fixed typing: Parser.__iter__ does not yield None

bugfix for commit 9e968ade6ef44c3caae5dbc88d9e311534dc8a7f
extended tests to make sure that all real CAN bus messages are now parsed

logreader bugfix: don't require a trailing space after remote frame in PCAN trace 2.0 and 2.1

bugfix for commit 9636c98e20b2f458f3cdc79529bdc21d493423e0
tests added in commit 4e5859df6d9445dd687f97a4c4e539c92cfe32b8

logreader: ignore error frames and warnings consistently

Before this commit the behavior was inconsistent.
Some formats parsed errors as DataFrame objects and some ignored errors because the regex did not match.
Now, no errors are parsed as DataFrame objects anymore.

issue.title: Expose a stable identifier or raw pointer for tokio::mpsc::Sender to support O(1) identity-based lookup in higher-level abstractions
issue.body:
Summary

Im working on an actor-style framework in Rust where each tokio::mpsc::Sender<T> represents an addressable mailbox. In order to implement zero-cost proxying and O(1) routing (e.g. forwarding messages to the correct actor instance in a proxy or fan-out scenario), I need a way to distinguish one Sender<T> from another without resorting to global registries or linear scans with is_same_channel. Currently the internal Arc that backs the sender is private, so there is no stable, hash-able identifier exposed in the public API.
Use Case

Actor proxies & fan-out: I generate code that wraps a single actor interface into multiple channels. When a proxy receives a reply it needs to forward back to the original sender in O(1) time.

Zero-cost abstractions: I want to avoid boxing or adding manual integer IDs into every ActorRef; ideally the channel handle itself would carry identity.

High-performance routing: In a large actor system or microservices mesh, linear scans over potentially thousands of mailboxes create unacceptable overhead.

Example

```
// Without a stable ID, proxies must scan a Vec and call is_same_channel():
for target in targets.iter() {
    if target.is_same_channel(&reply_to) {
        target.send(reply_msg).await?;
        break;
    }
}
// O(n) scantoo slow at scale.
```

Proposal

Add one of the following to tokio::mpsc::Sender<T>:

`fn id(&self) -> usize`
Returns a stable, unique identifier (e.g. pointer or hash of the internal Arc) that remains constant for the lifetime of the channel.

`fn as_ptr(&self) -> *const ()`
Exposes the raw, heap-allocated pointer of the internal Arc<Shared>. Users can then safely compare or hash that pointer for identity.

With either API, proxy code can build a HashMap<usize, Sender<T>> at setup time and do O(1) lookups for forwarding.
Alternatives Considered

Manual wrapper with atomic counter:

`struct IdentifiedSender<T> { id: usize, sender: Sender<T> }`

Works but pushes ID-management boilerplate onto every user and duplicates functionality that already exists internally in Tokio.

Unsafe Arc pointer extraction:
Transmute the Sender<T> wrapper to its hidden Arc<...> and call Arc::as_ptr(). Reliant on Tokio internals and brittle across versions.

Global registries:
Central HashMap<SenderKey, Sender<T>> guarded by a lockadds complexity, overhead, and global mutable state.

Impact & Backwards Compatibility

This would be a non-breaking API addition.

Existing code using is_same_channel continues working unchanged.

Lightweight to implement: under the hood, id() could call Arc::as_ptr(...) as usize or similar.

Enables higher-level libraries (actor frameworks, RPC proxies, debugging/tracing tools) to build more efficient routing on top of Tokio channels.

Thanks for considering this enhancement! Im happy to provide a PR or further details if the maintainers are open to adding a stableidentity API for Sender.

comment.body:
I'm not inclined to add it as a tokio feature.

> Works but pushes ID-management boilerplate onto every user

In my opinion, ID-management is not such complex, 3-party crates can implement it easily, and not all downstream of tokio needs a built-in sender id, this doesn't bring significant burdens to downstream.

You could try [`tokio_stream::StreamMap`] plus your own ID management, An atomic counter is not likely to make the code too much complex or become the bottleneck.

Since individual sender has already associated with an unique receiver, it is unusual to store the sender in the actor, normally, actor only stores receiver. Since we don't more context about your use case, it is hard to suggest more things.

[`tokio_stream::StreamMap`]: https://docs.rs/tokio-stream/0.1.17/tokio_stream/struct.StreamMap.html

pull_request.title: Replace individual Radix packages with `radix-ui`
pull_request.body: A few months ago we shipped a unified package for all Radix UI primitives. [The Radix docs now recommend using this package instead of individual primitive packages.](https://www.radix-ui.com/primitives/docs/overview/introduction#incremental-adoption) This prevents common issues like packages having conflicting dependencies which leads to potential bugs and bundle bloat. ---- > [!IMPORTANT] > Replace individual Radix UI component imports with a unified `radix-ui` package import across multiple files and update `package.json` accordingly. > > - **Imports**: > - Replace individual Radix UI component imports with `radix-ui` package import in `variant-filter.tsx`, `accordion.tsx`, and `alert-dialog.tsx`. > - Update `breadcrumb.tsx`, `button.tsx`, and `checkbox.tsx` to use `radix-ui` package. > - Modify `collapsible.tsx`, `command.tsx`, and `dialog.tsx` to import from `radix-ui`. > - Change `dropdown-menu.tsx`, `form.tsx`, and `label.tsx` to use `radix-ui`. > - Adjust `popover.tsx`, `progress.tsx`, and `radio-group.tsx` to import from `radix-ui`. > - Update `select.tsx`, `separator.tsx`, and `sheet.tsx` to use `radix-ui`. > - Modify `sidebar.tsx`, `tabs.tsx`, and `toast.tsx` to import from `radix-ui`. > - Change `tooltip.tsx` and `EvaluationTable.tsx` to use `radix-ui`. > - **Package Update**: > - Remove individual Radix UI packages from `package.json`. > - Add `radix-ui` package to `package.json`. > > This description was created by [](https://www.ellipsis.dev?ref=tensorzero%2Ftensorzero&utm_source=github&utm_medium=referral) for 6686c60eb5400193343105e2d71e8c88dc813e7f.
